8AABFB24300545B9A72A32ACE2DD745F.description:
Responds and recognizes naturally occurring events that reinforce the
ideas of change and the connections to care giving of living things.

376833D79E2041539499DFBB99E0A9A5.description: Engages in activities that promote a sense of contribution.

8546E958B86C4AE3827EF6FD35B1CF8E.description:
Can participate in improving their environment (e.g., pick up litter, recycle,
plant trees and flowers, conserve lights, water and paper).

DF29621053F54FAF85C56D77D8B8280A.description:
Begin to identify what families need to thrive (e.g., food, shelter, clothing,
love).

0B448B99DDD7425494CF643D4A6E6CE7.description:
Early Learning Expectation: People and Their Environment.
Children increase their understanding of the relationship
between people and their environment and begin to recognize the
importance of taking care of the resources in their environment.

1E943F9D8D6148E7A0E7BD81579A72DE.description: Make simple choices about how to spend money.

721D32A6D1E04E03A2F7716B875FF5F3.description:
Begin to understand that people pay for things with a representation of
money (e.g., currency, checks, debit cards, credit cards).

F865F51D284A45FDBC3393AB99699A3B.description: Can talk about some of the ways people earn a living.

BF124A2C98494C128057E4C842330FDA.description: Can talk about some of the workers and services in their community.

B23B9AB506B34102B13E67C25BA5193F.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Basic Ideas about Economics.
Children increase their understanding about how basic economic
concepts relate to their lives.

920D177065C34559A01A70BA1C8DFAA7.description: Show increasing respect for the rights of others.

AEBC2AD525414BCAA7EC03924A489223.description:
Can identify people (e.g., parents, teachers, bus drivers, lunchroom
helpers) who have authority in their home and early learning programs
(e.g., who helps them make rules, who tells them when they are breaking
a rule, who helps enforce rules).

3CB1F71E841B4FFB875E821719AA257F.description:
Begin to understand consequences of following and breaking (disobeying)
rules.

25405330B62E4D4698AD3C20DA7D2E51.description:
Grow in their understanding of the need for rules and boundaries in their
learning and social environment.

B4BF9031BE16453E9664EC56839E9BEB.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Why We Have Rules and Laws.
Children begin to learn about the reasons for rules and laws, the
importance of a democratic process, and the responsibilities of
being a member of a classroom, a family, and a community.

552AA9D781C4468DB6C9EE7A54CD4CCF.description:
Contribute to their community (classroom, school, neighborhood) as age
appropriate.

69A51F9F71764D7C945C170F5AC44325.description:
Demonstrate an increasing sense of belonging and awareness of their
roles as members of families, classrooms, and communities.

2693623E6D1A4CCCA6261B2747E97F82.description:
Gather information and learn new concepts through experimentation and
discovery, making connections what they already know.

D68DB819D8184AB7942AD5CFBA769573.description:
Show interest in nature and asks questions about what is seen and what
has changed (e.g., temperature, trees, sunlight) over time.

32355916597E4CDAB3B369A563EF7085.description: Can talk about recent and past events.

2457FED1CEBF448893F6391DA673E0D5.description: Use words to describe time (e.g., yesterday, today, tomorrow).

F2D4364B89E34844BF0490BFEA7E1CC4.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Understanding Time. Children show
growth in their understanding of the concept of time and begin
to realize that they are a part of a history, which includes people,
places, events, and stories about the present and the past.

F6265E551E2447B69738827BE44F406F.description: Participate in creating their own classroom celebrations.

7599361AA35B4FE8B9BC93410EFEC0B4.description:
Exhibit a growing capacity to self-regulate, demonstrate self-efficacy and
know acceptable boundaries.

CC74E2025C304452903D0A6006EE0465.description:
Grow in understanding of and respect for differences among cultural
groups, as well as their contributions to society.

65A71D8CB70E4BF88B376F6CFF1A7D72.description: Begin to recognize that people celebrate events in a variety of ways.

BE52E2DADFA44E028F522076E9DF1D1C.description:
Talk about ways members of a family can work together to help one
another.

8C2F550267CB40B2A9F5FA1793597D8F.description: Show an understanding of family and how families are alike and different.

A577B8740D674721B8F2542839E1D03B.description:
Begin to recognize themselves as unique individuals and become aware
of the uniqueness of others.

9F62E734F4A54EAFA3B1636A9C1B191B.description:
Can talk about personal information (e.g., name; family members; and, by
four, knowledge of personal traits, address, telephone number).

D5769D8067A34DF1961CB9E05ACFAC74.description:
Early Learning Expectation: How People Are Influenced. Children
begin to recognize that many different influences shape people’s
thinking and behavior.

8990640E04504A0B890AB7783AAC26BF.description: Use and understand words for location and direction.

03FB571C483B401D8A37791880683DDE.description:
Demonstrate a developing sense of respect for nature and its
components.

532E42B2DA994303BD5C147A84040B1F.description:
Engage in conversations that reflect experiences in and observations of
the environment.

61AF73021F3E48BDADCCB9A888463047.description:
Develop a sense of connectedness through the exploration of the natural
environment and materials, caring for animals or plants.

51019AB5E4214025B1B2287361FB6B95.description:
Extend information gained from books and stories or projects to learning
in the outdoor setting in which they live and play.

D7A77548AB304378B04F3AFCE5D0DB7B.description:
Explore the environment, experiment and play with natural materials,
explore the texture, sound and smells of nature.

6C87769682E545E19C433CB4DE143D04.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Relationship in Place. Children begin
to understand and interpret their relationship and place within
their own environment.

191178DF553C45EB8A05131A9B9A13B8.description:
Early
Learning in
the Social
Studies

0E1E6238F64643318728CE5B9A822151.description:
Talk about ways to be safe during bad weather and in outdoor
explorations.

7716C1FB85794C248D17A1861ED28513.description:
Begin to describe weather and its changing conditions (e.g., wind, rain,
snow, clouds).

8C46FAE82F3149429ABBD66811D38772.description:
Can talk about major features of the earth’s surface (streams, hills,
beaches) when found in the children’s neighborhood and neighborhoods
that they visit.

94CE7C5670104AB9BE96AFF8D7915FB2.description:
Can talk about the observable properties of earth materials (sand, rocks,
soil, water) and living organisms.

5A7FCBF501BC4FDDA5A2DE5C6193BDB3.description: Can talk about observable characteristics of different seasons.

45BC5010CC3D4831B14A9F1A153D066C.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Knowledge about the Earth. Children
show a beginning awareness of scientific knowledge related to
the earth.

F7136871F95D4CC78D3C14C80715B350.description:
Observe, describe and compare the motions of common
objects in terms of speed and direction (e.g., faster, slowest, up, down).

9DD23613CDE74C1D96BBBE70BE2B05EE.description:
Demonstrate greater knowledge and respect for their bodies (e.g.,
describe visible parts of the human body and their functions).

F6BD50E6F0084CDD9636454672A568A5.description:
Begin to describe the places in which familiar plants and animals in their
neighborhood live (e.g., city, drainage ponds, parks, fields, forests).

3A096051D339424F9E68307EDB16459F.description:
Begin to describe relationships among familiar plants and animals (e.g.,
caterpillars eat leaves).

0EFC4021566043A5B6C21D54DDD094A8.description:
Use observation skills to build awareness of plants and animals, their life
cycles (e.g., birth, aging, death) and basic needs (e.g., air, food, light,
rest).

09E64019DF3041689418938E9D49187B.description:
Begin to categorize living and non-living things in their environment based
on characteristics they can observe (e.g., texture, color, size, shape,
temperature, usefulness, weight).

A23FADB314DB4DED8E388772DF44E31D.description:
Demonstrate a growing ability to collect, talk about, and record
information about living and non-living things (e.g., through discussions,
drawings).

6936ECDB99FE406E8C87CD6989AA9EA5.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Living and Non-living Things. Children
show a beginning awareness of scientific knowledge related to
living and non-living things.

061492CF4E99460AA15BD6D8CFCC439C.description:
Begin to participate in simple investigations (e.g., asking questions
manipulating materials; anticipating what might happen next; testing their
observations to determine why things happen).

32B4D980BA6D49F4A7A79F9EC0CC103B.description:
Expand their observational skills (e.g., extending the time they
 observe, being able to describe and confirm their observations by using a
variety of resources).

13F5B049A66D472284F5E5AFEE512DB3.description:
Talk about their own predictions, explanations and generalizations based
on past and current experiences.

7181F37B474948F6B8E521E056E58415.description: Ask questions related to their own interest and observations.

93F149224F3548C383F7114DE968FD45.description:
Demonstrate curiosity about and interest in their natural environment
that leads them to confidently engage in activities related to science.

F34AC265DCE94A849BD6B8C8DC8E024B.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Observation and Inquiry. Children
develop positive attitudes and gain knowledge about science
through observation and active play.

C71CFCBFF9F743D194BB37F72A88134A.description:
Recognize patterns in various formats (e.g., things that can be seen,
heard, felt).

6D9597B269F041B0A884396AD93828A6.description:
Recognize, describe, copy, extend and create simple patterns with real
objects and through pictures.

FCCF8EB4FC274F4A95145041BB58BAEE.description:
Begin to build an understanding of directionality, order, and positions of
objects through the use of words (e.g., up, down, over, under, top, bottom,
inside, outside, in front of, behind).

0949D3631AFE4AAC9D4DE8C33A7A487E.description: Begin to recognize and appreciate geometric shapes in their environment.

70D808461DE0484298C528367C833F86.description:
Investigate and begin to predict the results of combining, subdividing, and
changing shapes.

FACF66A9B8BC4BF9961BEDC21ABE9DE7.description:
Can make models, draw, name, and/or classify common shapes and
verbally describe them in simple terms.

49743FD573714D5B9CB31DD41D1A54F4.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Geometry. Children build their visual
thinking skills through explorations with shape and the spaces in
their classrooms and neighborhoods.

FCA4440B86D34392B09F509290DBF1A6.description:
Begin to understand that tools (e.g., rulers, scales, counters) can be used
to measure properties of objects and amounts.

DFF7F006EF954EAABCF9E2511B301BC2.description:
Begin to use non-standard measures (e.g., length of hand) for length and
area of objects.

139085E86B6C4423A13094E382484A4A.description:
Use beginning skills of estimation in solving everyday measurement
problems (e.g., about how many cookies are needed for a small group of
children).

51FA65AE4E544040BE28C40BC6BCA231.description: Show an awareness of temperature as it affects their daily lives.

A451E643D4BD4CBE8DD365B57072868A.description:
Show an awareness of the concept of time, beginning with the recognition
of time as a sequence of events and how time plays a role in their daily
life (e.g., breakfast, snack, lunch, dinner).

A72172B6BDEE40E4A5C5C27C237F16AB.description: Begin to understand concepts of weight.

449444662E41407692D111B590183123.description: Show awareness that things in their environment can be measured.

37F9008C78384BC192787CF045005AF7.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Measuring. Children explore and
discover simple ways to measure.

7A684B81D6EE47E2BB827707ED909D1A.description:
Begin to understand that simple concrete and representational graphs are
ways of collecting, organizing, recording, and describing information.

A1AE5F4D98BA414AB202E574CC023C8D.description:
Recognize that the same group can be sorted and classified in more than
one way and describe why they would group or sequence in a particular
way.

AAD7D1B900E143108B819B1EF01D6D8F.description:
Can place objects or events in order, according to a given criterion (e.g.,
color, shape, size, time).

FFC073E81ACC429E8650DDE9C95B1B3F.description: Use simple estimation to make better guesses.

988B1CFED54143C38FEDF99110EA4799.description:
Can generate problems that involve predicting, collecting, and analyzing
information.

969328B731B44BE2BF0614C3F1753D6D.description:
Begin to develop the ability to solve problems involving joining,
separating, combining, and comparing amounts when using small
quantities of concrete materials.

5B855D2C02E3449CB9A96958278CCF33.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Simple Operations and Beginning
Algebraic Thinking. Children begin to develop skills of sorting and
organizing information, seeing patterns, and using information to
make predictions and solve new problems.

20419B57EC674AC591DC8199B6AAAC3A.description:
Develop an increasing ability to count in sequence up to ten and beyond,
typically referred to as “counting on.”

E0C65CE5872B422BABF862CBDAB7AA6D.description:
Understand how numbers can be used to label various aspects of their
lives (e.g., house number, phone number, ages of classmates).

151F40B17C2E419B99D813AF5AC3B062.description:
Use cardinal (e.g., one, two) and ordinal (e.g., first, second) numbers in
daily home and classroom life.

760CAEE5DF054C798E377D52F84B4182.description:
Show growth in understanding that number words and numerals
represent quantities.

8C3F7DD795E7428EB40687E3581A0729.description:
Show progress in linking number concepts, vocabulary, quantities and
written numerals in meaningful ways.

654739267DF3453BAFF021EC700C2FD8.description:
Recognize and match number symbols for small amounts with the
appropriate amounts (e.g., subitizing).

6A4873508F2A4756ADE63B89C2CCDBF5.description:
Make progress in moving beyond rote counting to an understanding of
conceptual counting (e.g., one-to-one correspondence).

4E1EF845EFB64834BFF99E73CF7AB74B.description:
Match, build, compare, and label amounts of objects and events (e.g.,
birthdays in the week) in their daily lives.

02293ABEF9EB47B99D04927147F83046.description:
Develop an increasing interest and awareness of numbers and counting
as a means for determining quantity and solving problems.

77221A0363BD4802B6AC8A20DD2476A4.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Counting and Cardinality. Children
extend their understanding of numbers and their relationship to
one another and things in the environment.

E7D2259791AA45E1B44446992A7A96A3.description:
Recognize patterns in various formats (e.g., things that can be seen,
heard, felt).

BF6AC256BF80472FAA03988E603A30F2.description:
Recognize, describe, copy, extend, and create simple patterns with real
objects and through pictures.

BCAC58274646478AB612A3CE5FA5824E.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Classification and Patterns. Children
begin to develop skills of recognizing, comparing and classifying
objects, relationships, events and patterns in their environment
and in everyday life.

F2E688E52CBD4346BFE76091D3FDAB5F.description:
Begin to describe comparative relationships (e.g., more/less/same
number of objects or quantities).

641FA80A760742CDBDD8C9687C4C8DCB.description:
Begin to recognize that information comes in many forms and can be
organized and displayed in different ways.

F4744AEDC0B84A4BB5F1D627E4877AFF.description:
Talk about their own mathematical explorations and discoveries using
simple mathematical language and quantity-related words.

B7FAD59C24A24891AD5748F79D65856E.description:
. Make progress from matching and recognizing number symbols to
reading and writing numerals.

41C51657A5824745845FF6B90018D47B.description: Begin to use symbols to represent real objects and quantities.

C3A575848E614B2AAF18B13227224C7B.description:
Begin to record their work with numbers in a variety of simple concrete
and pictorial formats, moving toward some use of number and other
mathematical symbols.

8BB9DF01A9AA440E97DA3521F40DD833.description:
Participate regularly in informal conversations about mathematical
concepts and number relationships.

800C013A2B0F451E889641E9466F695A.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Mathematical Literacy. Children begin
to use the language of mathematics by applying emerging skills
in representing, discussing, reading, writing, and listening (e.g.,
by translating a problem or activity into a new form; a picture,
diagram, model, symbol, or words).

164A026178134A3DA0612797DEC8340C.description:
Begin to generate problems that involve predicting, collecting, and
analyzing information and using simple estimation.

BA4E862D6EBC48C5B62AC3D8F22AB8BD.description:
Begin to talk about the processes and procedures they used to solve
concrete and simple mathematical situations.

CA0067051B7D4EA4BDCB4D342A2F267B.description:
Begin to develop and use various approaches to problem solving based
upon their trial and error experiences.

86E4DDFB3B4242B1A3DFA5569A25C256.description:
Generate new problems from every day mathematical situations and
use current knowledge and experience to solve them (e.g., distribute
crackers).

D3E55C6509184D4A85A90628F765ACBA.description:
Try to solve problems in their daily lives using mathematics (e.g., how
many napkins are needed).

0067046A06E54B95835637FA86A5B078.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Math Practices. Children begin to
develop processes and strategies for solving mathematical
problems.

D145C8EFC85C4FD19F6364CC610D8763.description:
Exhibit a growing capacity to self-regulate, demonstrate self-efficacy and
know acceptable boundaries.

BDCABA46333F45EC8BE8BB91EECF31DA.description:
Begin to try new activities with ‘just manageable’ risk (e.g., riding a
tricycle, climbing safely, jumping, exploring).

2302892CA03C4FE494F60732209B17C1.description:
Begin to learn the correct procedure for self-protection in emergency
situations (e.g., tornados, fire, storms, gun fire, chemical spills, avoidance
of other’s blood and vomit).

FCC805A279454FB49579234F7601A2D8.description:
Become aware of issues relative to personal safety (e.g., inappropriate
touching, good and bad secrets, learning how to say ‘No’ to inappropriate
touching by any other person, recognizing when to tell an adult about an
uncomfortable situation).

37E4C7E5F6B64BEEAE4205BC5029E500.description:
Begin to know important facts about themselves (e.g., address, phone
number, parent’s name).

E5A934D56458469B89A18C8DA0CF84FD.description: Identify persons to whom they can turn for help in an emergency situation.

79D78BA77B6F43FC8D035931DE219349.description:
Begin to learn appropriate safety procedures (e.g., in the home, at school,
as a pedestrian, outdoors, on the playground, with vehicles, with bicycles,
around bodies of water).

55925CB902794EC0B9F3C6FF4C4597AA.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Personal Safety. Children recognize
that they have a role in preventing accidents or potential
emergencies.

7A59D9C615ED4EE786E21C5AD8EB33D9.description:
Begin to become aware of activities, substances, and situations that may
pose potential hazards to health [e.g., smoking, poisonous materials,
edible, non-edible items (e.g., plants/berries), medications (appropriate
use of)].

7F8D4D7EBEDB4F9288C673E4B16FD726.description:
Can begin to recognize some symptoms of disease or health issues
(e.g., a sore throat is not a “sore neck”) and common instruments used in
diagnosing disease (e.g., thermometer, x-ray machines).

98E2A9E738004EB4A8480C66B63C269E.description:
Begin to be able to recognize activities that contribute to the spread of
communicable diseases (e.g., sharing of cups, eating utensils, hats,
clothing, foods).

9DC2850BEA9A4E968DC8F5AEF3632C0A.description: Develop an understanding of basic oral hygiene.

DEAE7A70B52C4316BEA3A0FBF927135A.description:
Talk about ways to prevent spreading germs and diseases to other
people.

CBEF1F74165C441AB3450858932BCDAA.description:
Grow in understanding of the importance of good health and its
relationship to physical activity.

72339EFDAE1349CDB510612C4D23A763.description:
Show growing independence in keeping themselves clean, personal care
when eating, dressing, washing hands, brushing teeth, use of tissues for
nose-blowing (and their disposal), and toileting.

3F20ECAE73C248469BA5339831675A4E.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Healthy Choices. Children begin to
have knowledge about and make age-appropriate healthy choices
in daily life.

CD99B22DFF8C4A84A6BEE1F9D4AFEDE9.description:
Become aware of foods that cause allergic reactions for some children
and/or other dietary needs or restrictions.

E2F8806FC4ED461693F9F4BD45A61CAD.description: Use age/developmentally-appropriate eating utensils safely and correctly.

005D6C1F6B714E16848E4216767E5C04.description:
Begin to listen to body signals of hunger and fullness, learn to choose
how much to eat at meals and snacks, and are able to convey their needs
for food to adults.

00EDB3F3B7FC4C9E91B4C5A2D3024D28.description:
Grow in their understanding of the importance of eating nutritious meals
and snacks at regular intervals, and how this relates to good health.

E1D562B1D2A342C088FF435B20419312.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Healthy Eating. Children become
aware of and begin to develop nutritional habits that contribute to
good health.

FF0F5B2A535F436EBA265CE2B01E78C5.description:
Demonstrate increasing ability to be together with others, in play or
intellectual learning opportunities and/or making positive efforts for the
good of all.

3A8602C38FBC402383439AF31C8AA3F4.description:
Begin to develop an appreciation and respect for the varying physical
abilities and capabilities of others.

7561EDC9386D45E6ADB9BA6044CB6063.description: Take pride in their own abilities and increase self-motivation.

D31BC4F27A8D4F719C60B61506A8AA2E.description:
Learn to cooperate with others through games and other activities and
actions that show a growing knowledge of the rights of others.

430EB46924C24DFD954ABCF940F4331D.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Positive Activity. Children participate
in activities that encourage self-motivation, emphasize
cooperation, and minimize competition.

E60D6DD375A94EB1ACA0DD6835B7B458.description:
Use fine motor skills they are learning in daily activities (e.g., dressing
themselves).

8910BE2B769C427381482BD29B9C70B2.description:
Develop and refine motor control and coordination, eye-hand
coordination, finger/thumb and whole-hand strength coordination and
endurance using a variety of age-appropriate tools (e.g., scissors, pencils,
markers, crayons, blocks, putting together puzzles, using a variety of
technology).

E52063E7B70B44B58EFC034FC661BFDC.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Fine Motor Development. Children
experience growth in fine motor development and use small
muscles to improve a variety of fine motor skills both in structured
and unstructured settings.

2885F5BC3C2C48978D99B419B96579F8.description:
Exhibit a growing capacity to self-regulate, demonstrate self-efficacy and
know acceptable boundaries (e.g., riding a tricycle or bike, using their
bodies in helpful vs. hurtful ways, being a ‘leader’ in a game).

44615EF5038E402A89DB49E1CA26C94D.description:
Show increasing abilities to coordinate movements (e.g., throwing,
catching, kicking, bouncing balls, using the slide and swing) in order to
build strength, flexibility, balance, and stamina.

1B3C03DD5B254493A0A1DEECED5AAED9.description: Show their ability to use different body parts in a rhythmic pattern.

EB4F173CCEF84AC6B8E2FA65F5624025.description:
Begin or continue to develop traveling movements such as walking,
climbing, running, jumping, hopping, skipping, marching, and galloping.

E5C620CDC01D4CD3BBA6DBAF36DDCFCB.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Gross Motor Development. Children
experience growth in gross motor development and use large
muscles to improve a variety of gross motor skills in a variety of
both structured and unstructured and planned and spontaneous
settings.

DF0D1BC8778C4398BA7887CD29CE8549.description:
Increasingly develops greater self-awareness; identifies his or her own
interest and strengths.

C8F178B5030E4DAFBF43863BF284765D.description:
Participate actively and on a regular basis, in games, outdoor play, and
other forms of vigorous exercise that enhance physical fitness.

091207D0E8D34183A14D6CAA29E328C7.description:
Begin to understand spatial awareness for themselves, others, and their
environment.

0167AE2A4462466893F1B4A325908547.description: Begin to recognize and learn the names of body parts.

05993BDEAD7C4B7BB192A4DC214CFED4.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Body Control and Activity. Children
increase their ability to understand and control their bodies and
learn that regular physical activity can enhance their overall
physical, social, and mental health.

D796631A338747F09770F87D69FDC0AF.description:
Demonstrate an increasing sense of belonging and awareness of their
role as a member of a family, classroom, and community.

9BFEB1F878AB4793870DDFA93B5285FF.description: Participate successfully as a group member.

5B200823BBFA4BE2978FE62A3199FA8F.description: Show progress in developing and keeping friendships.

4262906ED3C44D4FADE2CCEFAFFFFA51.description: Show increasing respect for the rights of others.

3FEEDDBD4DC84C0884B794A4463D241D.description: Increase their capacity to take another’s perspective.

B7F1BE38FD344B3CA55EFCDD8DD0EC4F.description:
Recognize similarities and differences in people (gender, family, race,
culture, language).

776CF97FA4CE4DEEA36C206D331B6E2E.description:
Begin to develop and practice the use of problem-solving and conflict
resolution skills.

86F34DEDD082451687A42BAD5D864CB0.description:
Increase their ability to initiate and sustain age-appropriate interactions
with peers and adults.

A79B332563134C49AAA5B88357676544.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Relationships with Others. Children
develop healthy relationships with other children and adults.

0887027E5DB94A16BCBD743D98B88D5B.description: Manage transitions and follow routines most of the time.

181891FB12D14AB3AA1FA628444D1B64.description: Begin to know when and how to seek help from an adult or peer.

345260C8C31842D0A9C5D10546D4AD8B.description:

of the time.

640CF6FDE7D04C22A6E1DADA251FD5F6.description:
Grow in their ability to follow simple, clear, and consistent directions
and rules.

9A780C7958FE4FD1B34DF992AC12CF35.description:
Grow in their capacity to avoid harming themselves, others, or things
around them when expressing feelings, needs and opinions.

F2CD5C73320440AE92CD8763337A32BA.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Expressing Emotions. Children show
increasing ability to regulate how they express their emotions.

4A2FD826D37E4EC4B854DEF9CE3B6E94.description: Identify a variety of feelings and moods (in themselves and others).

FB223E949C524521B0F3DC36FE225B9A.description:

race, culture and language.

8FB4B3D580F74F64B923185F6C8D54A4.description:
Demonstrate growing confidence in expressing their feelings, needs and
opinions

6E1ED95042FD40F0A603BFC1BAA3D265.description: Show an emerging sense of self-awareness.

AA605DDF79B647609477822EB3666E98.description:

develop and exhibit a healthy sense of self.

Social,
Emotional
and Physical
Health and
Development

BC4FBEE0CB0D40A7A9C8D133765DDF97.description: Use adaptive devices to operate a software program as necessary.

equipment.

6A6E120940B64631B02107E46B9750D2.description: Recognize and name the major parts of a computer and other devices.

Children begin to learn to use and talk about technology tools
appropriately.

E9C5BFDA6E124C91A760E3C613A6975A.description:
Know to use the computer only when an adult is supervising and to inform
a trusted adult if anything on the Internet creates discomfort.

04A63693E3FB48169598D36B60FEC5EC.description:
Identify personal information that should not be shared on the Internet or
the phone (e.g., name, address, phone).

887DCA04DB8741919246445139D5B5B2.description:
Identify the Michigan Cyber Safety Initiative’s three rules (Keep Safe,
Keep Away, Keep Telling).

4DE560DDC5C74E0BABF15C4788D627C6.description:
Begin to understand how technology can be used inappropriately (e.g.,
using another’s cell phone without permission, using the Internet without
supervision).

B87C49A9B36B41D9A3D0D7253C7109C4.description:
Begin to state and follow rules for safe use of the computer and other
technology tools.

7803B56ABA3D4B0D9AA4ECCB08BD3998.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Digital Citizenship. Children begin
to understand how technology can be used appropriately or
inappropriately.

524C50F80409478EB07D706CA520ED93.description:
When faced with a problem, suggest the use of technology tool to solve
the problem (e.g., take a picture of a block creation to show parents, find
out the size of a dinosaur).

CAD689F9771749EBB64CCF1FF019DD7B.description:
Talk, ask questions, solve problems and share ideas with peers and
adults, when using computers and other technology tools.

3924FE9588C149AD847948FC132FD7F5.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Critical Thinking, Problem Solving,
and Decision Making. Children can explain some ways that
technology can be used to solve problems.

64686E04E713461D9BC209A7D4F97CDF.description:
Respond to information found on the internet in developmentally
appropriate ways (e.g., tell what they learned, draw a picture, use the
information to accomplish a task).

427F52CA986E48BFAFB315E3FFACF7A6.description:
Understand that the internet can be used to locate information as well as
for entertainment.

745D8C5DADD8435BA50E3F226DDA2657.description: Begin to be able to navigate developmentally appropriate websites.

7E14EA75CD8E4879B07CBB205261A789.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Research and Information Literacy.
With adult support and supervision, children interact with
developmentally appropriate Internet based resources. With adult
support, children use developmentally appropriate digital resources
to locate and use information relating to a topic under study.

750B6DAAC8694D1C9D8611FC4E2B5047.description:
Work with one or more other children to plan and create a product with a
technology tool.

3AFA9AF742AB4FBB8BEB132132087F2A.description:
Respond to other children’s technology products vocally or within the
technology tool.

201BFE6CC8E74A449995282D890FBA76.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Communication and Collaboration.
Children work together when using developmentally appropriate
digital tools.

8028DC04F92F4A418AACC41AB580D8AB.description:

communicating feelings and ideas.

72AE008702D54560913FCBDCBD0BB922.description: Understand that technology tools can be used throughout the day.

EE88DC21FAB04EDDB5E9C9CDFCD7E02E.description:
Can describe and creatively use a variety of technological tools
independently or with peer or adult help.

118003DF9ABD4C9D9E62A51C1F9BCCAB.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Creativity and Innovation. Children
use a variety of developmentally appropriate digital tools to learn
and create.

9D2F453FCDD4402681ECB0CD7F142A47.description:

D8C41A6F01354D49B4374DD266285647.description: Use drawing and emergent writing together.

3E48F7567EE744079971AFE7272EC037.description:

Continue to use and build home language as needed to build

4A46D5770D274A04863CD297FAE52E2F.description:

A03ACD8A29C54CF6B260045DE1948574.description: Demonstrate a beginning of phonological awareness and phonics.

Demonstrate increased understanding of simple words and phrases used

Observe peers and adults with increasing attention to understand

346CB9DB449B4A969DBCA510557A6453.description:

9A19A63AC68C433BB86E83B56462D06B.description:
Become aware of alternate and various forms of communication (e.g.,

84CB1E797CC84DF3829072C5E7B4B3B7.description:

people communicate in a variety of ways.

Show growth in eagerness to learn about and discuss a growing range of

4E23AB74A8FB4FB4B4D0F4FCAB495DEA.description:
Approach tasks and activities with increased flexibility, imagination,

6A180B85118648E4907E46D16BA9B52D.description: Make connections with situations or events, people or stories.

curiosity).

information, and to expand their curiosity.

C1F16EADA72D49F4973A210EB201E371.description:

Children develop positive attitudes about themselves as literate
beings — as readers, writers, speakers, viewers, and listeners.

to gain information, for pleasure, to add to their understanding of written
materials, for visual cues or creative purposes).

3D6871ED0B93407795142B2B40A1C71F.description:

Materials. Children begin to develop strategies that assist them in
viewing a variety of images and multimedia materials effectively
and critically.

5E0C9F521100441FAF4841181C033E75.description:
Show progress in listening to and understanding both their home

6C1B8AFFA0D34D109B25465DC1229272.description:

gestures.

99CEE378E7944891868DEEA79B4350C3.description:

25BD982774F34C1796C2C869EA259488.description: Show progress in listening to and following spoken directions.

3D00BBF46BFD421F95237B710D34E2DD.description:

BD5740A8D7E14E75B5B8899C5FD93EC1.description:

24A6E3EEA9324371A0031920A9E3D7B2.description:

A26278C957A04D6B89DB553A0F582AF0.description:

67F14A05DE3640F7A48D2820D31F074B.description:

5B0A646B3CB043B194C818971BCEF887.description: Show increasing comfort and confidence when speaking.

A50D4285793C41A59074DE1DB72AADBD.description:

Early Learning Expectation: Spoken Language: Expressive.

8C0BD0EE6DEA4694B77A0867BE5A0869.description:
Show beginnings of a sense of the need to look over and modify their

CE1D6433C7D7483387BBDAA0F6AD774E.description:

7D5D652F51E5453BA44F72E921FD8803.description: Begin to write familiar words such as their own name.

1B64DAF8DC664CEFBCCF7C549E2628FE.description:

9EF7BBA11B594BD59D12B5FDD8204D8F.description:

22B4D12B77EF4E44A24AAC33F90B847D.description:

1E5B609F2A9A4AC48FD2A6CA38BD532B.description:

45EC3395DD0F4B78AEAD4BACF28FDB0C.description:

EC442B7A835A47BB9691F964F726E593.description:

BC73BCCD7FEE4BB485F3426AD97B9580.description: Understand that ideas can be written and then read by others.

A69A1FB3DC994F528E34533CB3AFE2A6.description:

C7BCF4BBF80442BAB26EF718104C4A2C.description:

9CD131673B914DD7B3CF5F710D6C7A13.description:

6BC8013ECDC546FBAFB71BCB28D822BC.description:

0AF12A265F484C808F42E2935BE5CED6.description:

CEDF70C63263453FA6CD0A3F4CDF68A5.description:

9BBC803E91934D33B5DE3F2617D46EEA.description: Begin to develop creative arts vocabulary.

C9575583670C4DF783DF0EE04C9B0DDF.description:

D4EE2B519E6844CC9768A310C2EB9FDB.description: Use the creative arts to express their view of the world.

A0CEABF8533945C6B43A6E6BEBD39F64.description:

AAB9C4C6EA53409FB3DB95E714936028.description:

23F2489DAA8A49F08010F2A30B38ED3A.description: Develop healthy self-concepts through creative arts experiences.

8C892E7A01784006B170FAB943968266.description: Begin to differentiate between fantasy and reality.

BEF2B551872A40E5B16E85D90BF7519C.description:

6E6CCDD6AD684A38A25031CDEE3DABA7.description:

D4620B18B12D4891A681A3A9FA049DCC.description:

6C3F527C06944D6D9E1622344E92FA15.description:

8B81FEEF1B0E4F26855F1159DB8DD3BA.description:
Begin to understand and demonstrate the components of music (e.g., tone,

C5FF48067BA9420EAE270D64CE91AD74.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Instrumental and Vocal Music.
Children show how they feel, what they think, and what they

047D97193034485D944EBF2141027B0D.description: Create representations that contain increasing detail.

EC493EA17843473780DA5A33DACF2CA0.description:
Begin to show growing awareness and use of artistic elements (e.g., line,

11390D61F9F94B8EAA38DCBE504C108A.description:
Begin to plan and carry out projects and activities with increasing
persistence.

01BE16B00A864D75AEF3020359424834.description:

5C577FD808DC47F687703F15A635A330.description:
Show an increasing ability to follow simple, clear and consistent directions

27DED39B111B4ABEB21AE349D118E4CF.description:

Exhibit a growing capacity to self-regulate, demonstrate self-efficacy and
know acceptable boundaries.

71CCBC1D11C74C8B87D2438C53044D33.description:
Demonstrate positive feelings about their own gender, family, race, culture
and language.

A6914ABD667C4779BD5B7D8393C2DEC1.description:
Can resist and effectively respond to inappropriate peer pressure (as age
appropriate).

2D2435430ABD476BA4628AD7C5D2CBFD.description:
Demonstrate the ability to care. Can respond with sensitivity or sincerity,
later empathy.

C9AACEDD6C81432387D8098DF4C50929.description:
Increasingly develop greater self-awareness; identify their own interests
and strengths. Can be comfortable choosing to be alone.

A4B9D0F76DC7481895C0A818C50DE1D2.description: Resolve (or attempt to resolve) conflicts respectfully.

F0FD68A383854EEA94A75BF794C0C7A7.description:
Use positive communication and behaviors (do not mock, belittle, or
exclude others).

01CA7ABE7B814090B3EB363E30ECE31B.description:
Cope with stress in a reasonable and age appropriate way. Grow in their
capacity to avoid harming themselves, others, or things around them
when expressing feelings, needs and opinions.

E241EF3E19BB4C5D965E98764ABEDBF0.description:
Extend offers (gestures, words) of help to peers or adults, to help them
feel that they belong to the group.

E09DC9BCD72D4D1290C11FBA3F388FA6.description: Show increasing respect for the rights of others.

6D533BEC7A2745E08C498BFBE20DB263.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Respect for Self and Others — Mental
and Behavioral Health. Children exhibit a growing regard for
one’s mind and capacity to learn; demonstrate the capacity of
consideration for others; show a growing capacity to self-regulate
and demonstrate self-efficacy.

2F1EBD1E50D049FB8590D505F0921C42.description:
Demonstrate an increasing sense of belonging and awareness of their
roles as members of families, classrooms and communities.

24F6CB3C39C14223A619A4891578E307.description: Contribute individual strengths, imagination or interests to a group.

AF0974890E2540FFAE4782318BF74119.description:
Can join a community of learners in person and digitally as appropriate;
enjoy mutual engagement.

5ECFAA44076548539A12E96D6E44A241.description:
Show an increasing capacity to consider or take into account another’s
perspective.

BA0528D7D69C40F98D3C79210724CB9E.description:
Recognize respectfully the similarities and differences in people (gender,
family, race, culture, language).

1315B90D7860426F93C35614385B29C3.description:
Begin to develop and practice the use of problem-solving and conflict
resolution skills.

B5AEDD9EE0BB411FA349B3B21D44ACE9.description:
Show an increasing ability to initiate and sustain age-appropriate play and
interactions with peers and adults.

6421FB933D2F49CEACA249D5EB6AEFEE.description: Learn from and through relationships and interactions.

758CC37D1497451A99C52E0ACF875305.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Participation-Cooperation-PlayNetworking-Contribution.
Demonstrate increasing ability to be
together with others, in play or intellectual learning opportunities
and/or making positive efforts for the good of all; join a community
of learners in person and digitally as appropriate.

6DBE8CB14B45435E94F1DC3EFFF559C1.description:
Show an increasing ability to observe detail and attributes of objects,
activities, and processes.

1FE42ABD80D44CFA831282D2029B6557.description:
Share through words or actions the acquisition of increasingly
complex concepts.

F8D32F6765924474B4547997DE1A04D8.description:
Gather information and learn new concepts through experimentation and
discovery, making connections to what they already know.

3A693B07FE7448EB9D4E1091CAAD6268.description: Attempt a variety of ways of solving problems.

516F1C0A8FD5449AAABECBC87DA4779A.description:
Show an increasing ability to predict outcomes by checking out and
evaluating their predictions.

1BF5311A2DD8439AA30089A6A2FD54A9.description:
Show an increasing ability to ask questions appropriate to the
circumstance.

2DD752D762824DF98928258DF51C9D04.description: Begin to hypothesize or make inferences.

1710B3C849BD41C1B2FFEC8838E24947.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Reasoning-Problem Solving-Reflection.
Children demonstrate a growing capacity to make meaning, using
one’s habits of mind to find a solution or figure something out.

D92121D742D14046A2CFE8B670CCE392.description: Begin to set aside fear of failure when self-initiating new tasks.

919EEDFE193C47ED9835E052FD6F8330.description:
Use stories and literature to pretend, play, act or take on characters to
help establish their situation or reality.

D1CEF60DA1E94845A322FC61E2D173F4.description: Begin to organize projects or play; make and carryout plans.

4B98B01EA3644A35A67396E514DEF0D0.description: Meet new and varied tasks with energy, creativity and interest.

9310B5DD37AE477F9F34CFAF57AE083A.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Resilience-Optimism-Confidence.
Children demonstrate the capacity to cope with change, persist,
move ahead with spirit, vitality and a growing belief in one’s ability
to realize a goal.

8E24836B4F40438B872B9CC8168BBE46.description:
Re-conceptualize or re-design (block structures, shapes, art materials,
digital images, simple graphs).

EBB5059F9F0A43D5916E67BE3EE35D3E.description:
Choose to take opportunities to explore, investigate or question
in any domain.

177A63F3E7654277AFCDD0FCC9E8D680.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Curiosity–Inquiry-QuestioningTinkering-Risk
Taking. Children demonstrate an interest and
eagerness in seeking information (e.g., be able to see things from
a different perspective, fiddling with something to figure it out or
attempting a reasonable solution).

D6B45F52FA0447EA821FBCC8DE4E2163.description: Explore, experiment and ask questions freely.

12F36A655A724FC5B71FF3A91C62A74B.description:
Show growing capacity to maintain concentration in spite of distractions
and interruptions.

F396574154A4467AB65B1BA12EF1BFDE.description:
Demonstrate increasing ability to set goals and to develop and follow
through on plans.

1811610C5ADA4C899BEE1BAE937DB4F9.description:
Grow in abilities to persist in and complete a variety of tasks, activities,
projects and experiences.

F3B0C811A53648E8BCDBF89B4CF3424B.description: Initiate ‘shared thinking’ with peers and adults.

205B8CE1788E4927A0356A9313670CB5.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Initiative-Engagement-PersistenceAttentiveness.
Children demonstrate the quality of showing
interest in learning; pursue learning independently.

57A3D2CA186A4B589800583C554785BE.description:
Grow in eagerness to learn about and discuss a growing range of topics,
ideas, and tasks.

932D3F4877774667BEC2C18BAC65529D.description:
Approach tasks and activities with increased flexibility, imagination,
inventiveness, and confidence.

B3E1A0A5EE544C9C86EBD95ECC50D545.description:
Expand current knowledge onto a new solution, new thinking or new
concept.

DE39F913A990430B9A9DCE774E34D436.description:
Propose or explore possibilities to suggest what an object or idea might
be ‘otherwise.’

574C2FBB92364DB5BAB98D2FED7F623D.description: Create new images or express ideas.

E114C522DC32411199EFE3593896A9B2.description: Make connections with situations or events, people or stories.

532158F577C444F8A9DDE2AB9E1AE056.description: Can be playful with peers and adults.

69C8CF72AF3349C4A141ED857ED0C944.description:
Early Learning Expectation: Creativity-Imagination-Visualization.
Children demonstrate a growing ability to use originality or vision
when approaching learning; use imagination, show ability to
visualize a solution or new concept.
